    dek: `Throw out the actor's playbook. The vocabulary of motivation, objectives, and emotional beats that works on trained actors will get you a deer-in-headlights stare from a non-actor. Directing a real person is a fundamentally different craft — you give them actions, not feelings; situations, not subtext; and above all, you build the trust that lets them forget the camera. Here's the whole approach.`,
    body: `
    <p>If you've studied directing actors, you've learned a rich vocabulary — objectives, motivations, subtext, emotional beats, the character's inner life. Now unlearn it, at least for non-actors, because that language assumes a trained instrument that can translate abstract ideas into performance, and a non-actor has no such instrument. Tell a real person "your objective in this scene is to win her forgiveness while masking your guilt," and they'll freeze, because you've asked them to do something they have no technique for. The core principle of directing non-actors is the inverse of directing actors: <strong>don't ask them to feel or portray anything — give them something concrete and real to do, and let the truth arise from the doing.</strong> You're not coaxing out a performance; you're setting up a real situation and capturing how a real person genuinely behaves in it. Master that shift and directing non-actors becomes not just possible but joyful.</p>

    <h2>The principles of directing a real person</h2>

    <p>How to actually direct someone with no training:</p>

    <ul class="spec-list">
      <li><b>Give actions, not emotions.</b> Never "be sad" or "show anger." Instead: "pick up the photo and look at it," "keep trying to leave while he blocks the door." Concrete physical actions produce real behavior; emotion directions produce fake acting.</li>
      <li><b>Create the situation, don't describe the feeling.</b> Set up a real or believable circumstance and let the person react honestly, rather than explaining what the character feels. Reality does the work.</li>
      <li><b>Build trust first, always.</b> A non-actor performs for someone they trust and feel safe with. Spend real time with them before you shoot; be warm, patient, and encouraging. A relaxed, trusting person gives truth; an anxious one gives nothing.</li>
      <li><b>Keep it simple and concrete.</b> Short, clear, physical, positive directions — one thing at a time. Abstract or layered notes overwhelm; simple actionable ones land.</li>
      <li><b>Never make them feel they're failing.</b> The instant a non-actor feels they're "getting it wrong," they tense up and it's over. Stay positive, reassure constantly, and hide the stakes. Their comfort is a technical requirement.</li>
      <li><b>Talk them through it live.</b> Many non-actors respond far better to quiet, real-time guidance during the take ("now you notice the door's open... go and check it") than to notes beforehand. You remove your voice later.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Your job is to protect their reality</h2>

    <p>Underneath all these techniques is one unifying idea about your role: <strong>when directing a non-actor, your job is to create and protect the conditions in which a real person can be real, and then capture it.</strong> A non-actor's superpower is their unselfconscious truth, and that truth is fragile — it evaporates the moment they become aware of "acting," feel judged, get confused by a complex note, or sense you're unhappy with them. So much of your directing is really about <em>removing the things that make them self-conscious</em>: the intimidating vocabulary, the pressure to perform, the fear of failing, the awareness of the machinery around them. You build trust so they feel safe. You give them simple actions so they always know what to do. You keep the mood warm and low-pressure so they never tense up. You engineer real situations so their behavior is genuine, not performed. And then you get out of the way and let the camera catch the truth. This is a humbler, more patient kind of directing than shaping a trained actor's performance — you're less a sculptor imposing a vision and more a gardener creating the conditions for something real to grow. It also requires reading the individual person: every non-actor is different, and part of the craft is figuring out what unlocks <em>this</em> particular real human — some need lots of reassurance, some need a concrete task, some are best when they don't even fully realize they're being filmed. Pay attention, adapt, and stay endlessly patient, because the payoff is worth it: when you get the conditions right and a real person relaxes into genuine behavior in front of your lens, you capture a truth that no amount of directing a trained actor can manufacture. That's the whole art of directing non-actors, and everything in the next two chapters — getting a natural performance, the specific on-set techniques — is a deeper application of this one principle. You don't direct a non-actor to perform. You create a reality and protect it long enough to film.</p>

    <div class="pullquote">Don't ask a non-actor to feel or portray anything — give them something real to do, and let the truth arise from the doing. You create a reality and protect it long enough to film.</div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
      <p>The day I stopped giving non-actors emotional notes and started giving them actions, everything changed. Instead of "you're heartbroken here," I'd say "fold the laundry, and when you find his shirt, decide what to do with it" — and the heartbreak would arrive on its own, real and unforced, because the person was actually doing something real. My whole job became creating true little situations and protecting the person's comfort so they'd relax into them. I direct non-actors like a gardener now, not a sculptor: set up the right conditions, stay warm and patient, and let something real grow in front of the lens.</p>
    </div>
`,
